The stock market's dizzying gyrations during the past few days have made a lot of individual investors wish@#%^&*1
they could buy some sort of insurance.@#%^&*1
After all, they won't soon forget the stock bargains@#%^&*2
that became available after the October 1987 crash.@#%^&*2
But@#%^&*3
while they want to be on the alert for similar buying opportunities now,@#%^&*3
they're afraid of being hammered by another terrifying plunge.@#%^&*3
The solution, at least for some investors, may be a hedging technique@#%^&*4
that's well known to players in the stock-options market.@#%^&*4
Called a "married put,"@#%^&*5
the technique is carried out@#%^&*5
by purchasing a stock@#%^&*5
and simultaneously buying a put option on that stock.@#%^&*5
It's like "fire insurance,"@#%^&*6
says Harrison Roth, the senior options strategist at Cowen & Co.@#%^&*6
Because a put option gives its owner the right, but not the obligation,@#%^&*7
to sell a fixed number of shares of the stock at a stated price on or before the option's expiration date,@#%^&*7
the investor is protected against a sudden drop in the stock's price.@#%^&*7
But most investment advisers don't recommend using married puts all the time.@#%^&*8
That's because the cost of buying put options eats into an investor's profit@#%^&*9
when stock prices rise.@#%^&*9
"This is the type of fire insurance@#%^&*10
you only buy@#%^&*10
when the nearby woods are on fire,"@#%^&*10
says Mr. Roth.@#%^&*10
"You always want your house insured,@#%^&*11
but you don't always feel the need@#%^&*11
for your investments to be insured."@#%^&*11
In addition to hedging new stock purchases,@#%^&*12
the married-put technique can be used to protect stocks@#%^&*12
that an investor already owns.@#%^&*12
In either case, the investor faces three possible outcomes:@#%^&*13
-- If the stock goes up in price between now and the put's expiration date,@#%^&*13
the put will probably expire worthless.@#%^&*13
The investor will be out the cost of the put,@#%^&*14
which is called the "premium,"@#%^&*14
and this loss will reduce the stock-market profit.@#%^&*14
-- If the stock stays at the same price between now and the put's expiration date,@#%^&*15
the investor's loss will be limited to the cost of the put, less any amount@#%^&*15
realized from a closing sale of the put.@#%^&*15
The worst-case scenario would be if the put expires worthless.@#%^&*16
-- If the price of the stock declines,@#%^&*17
the put will increase in value.@#%^&*17
Once the stock price is less than the exercise price, or "strike price," of the put,@#%^&*18
the gain will match the loss on the stock dollar for dollar.@#%^&*18
The put establishes a minimum selling price for the stock during its life.@#%^&*19
When a stock falls below the put's strike price,@#%^&*20
the investor simply sells the stock at a loss@#%^&*20
and simultaneously sells the put at a profit.@#%^&*20
Or, the investor can exercise the put,@#%^&*21
by tendering the stock to his or her broker in return for payment from another investor@#%^&*21
who has sold a put on the same stock.@#%^&*21
Brokers handle such transactions through the Options Clearing Corp.,@#%^&*22
which guarantees all option trades.@#%^&*22
