Normally,@#%^&*40
once the underlying investment is suspended from trading,@#%^&*40
the options on those investments also don't trade.@#%^&*40
Ultimately, whether the insurance@#%^&*41
provided@#%^&*41
by purchasing puts@#%^&*41
is worthwhile depends on the cost of the options.@#%^&*41
That cost rises in times of high market volatility.@#%^&*42
But it still might be cheaper@#%^&*43
than taking a major hit.@#%^&*43
The protection from using married puts is clearly superior to that@#%^&*44
afforded by another options strategy@#%^&*44
some investors consider using during troubled times:@#%^&*44
selling call options on stocks@#%^&*44
the investor owns.@#%^&*44
A call option is similar to a put,@#%^&*45
except that it gives its owner the right@#%^&*45
to buy shares at a stated price until expiration.@#%^&*45
Selling a call option gives an investor a small buffer against a stock-market decline.@#%^&*46
That's because it reduces the cost of the stock by the amount of premium@#%^&*47
received from the sale of the call.@#%^&*47
But@#%^&*48
if the price of the stock rises above the strike price of the option,@#%^&*48
the stock is almost certain to be called away.@#%^&*48
And in that case, the investor misses out on any major upside gain.@#%^&*49
